      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". from the Law of God. The speaker has apparently in view here all such defections from the Law as would entail punishment on the convicted offender. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [6], indeed, the crime described here as \"that which is wrong\" (margin, \"falling away\") is specially the crime of apostasy to idolatry; but the word (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "סָרָה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), though usually expressing apostasy from Jehovah, has properly the general sense of a deflection from a prescribed course (from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "סוּר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to go off, to go aside), and so may describe any departure from what is constituted right. Deuteronomy 19:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
