  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Punishment of a False Witness. - To secure life and property against false accusations, Moses lays down the law in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 19:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that one witness only was not \"to rise up against any one with reference to any crime or sin, with every sin that one commits\" (i.e., to appear before a court of justice, or be accepted as sufficient), but everything was to be established upon the testimony of two or three witnesses. The rule laid down in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 35:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for capital crimes, is raised hereby into a law of general application (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 35:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). קוּם (in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 19:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), to stand, i.e., to acquire legal force. - But as it was not always possible to bring forward two or three witnesses, and the statement of one witness could not well be disregarded, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 19:16-18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Moses refers accusations of this kind to the higher tribunal at the sanctuary for investigation and decision, and appoints the same punishment for a false witness, which would have fallen upon the person accused, if he had been convicted of the crime with which he was charged. סרה בּו לענות, \"to testify against his departure,\" sc., from the law of God, not merely falling away into idolatry (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but any kind of crime, as we may gather from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 19:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which would be visited with capital punishment. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
